docs/source/content-spec.md:3392:## 29. Final Summary
docs/source/content-spec.md:3403:- What will be recorded for audit?
docs/source/content-spec.md:3405:The system should therefore use precise vocabulary, reason-based decisions, clear status labels, explicit blockers, borrower-friendly communication and version-controlled templates. This content specification should be treated as the single source of truth for UI copy, notification copy, generated document structure and content governance during product design and implementation.
docs/source/component-spec.md:1:# component-spec.md
docs/source/component-spec.md:3:# SFPCL Member Credit Administration & Settlement — Detailed Component Specification
docs/source/component-spec.md:5:## 1. Document Control
docs/source/component-spec.md:12:| Business process | Member credit administration, loan sanction, documentation, disbursement, monitoring, recovery and settlement |
docs/source/component-spec.md:15:| Document purpose | Define the reusable functional, UI, workflow, document, data, notification and control components required to build the loan management system in a consistent, auditable and SOP-aligned manner |
docs/source/component-spec.md:20:## 2. Purpose of This Component Specification
docs/source/component-spec.md:22:This document defines the component layer for a digital system that implements SFPCL's member credit administration process.
docs/source/component-spec.md:31:The purpose of this document is to ensure that the product is built using a controlled set of reusable, role-aware and audit-friendly components instead of one-off screens. Each component must support the lending process described in the SOP: application, eligibility, appraisal, sanction, documentation, stamping, SAP setup, disbursement, repayment, monitoring, default handling, recovery, closure, compliance and audit.
docs/source/component-spec.md:35:## 3. Component Design Principles
docs/source/component-spec.md:39:### 3.1 Compliance First
docs/source/component-spec.md:41:The system handles regulated lending-like activity by a Producer Company to its members. Components must not optimise for speed at the cost of control. Components should prevent unauthorised disbursement, incomplete documentation, missing KYC, unapproved exceptions, untracked recovery actions and informal use of security documents.
docs/source/component-spec.md:43:### 3.2 Role-Aware Behaviour
docs/source/component-spec.md:47:### 3.3 Maker-Checker by Default
docs/source/component-spec.md:57:Examples include appraisal submission, sanction approval, document checklist approval, SAP customer code confirmation, disbursement execution, exception approval and recovery approval.
docs/source/component-spec.md:59:### 3.4 Traceable State Changes
docs/source/component-spec.md:61:Every important state transition must create an audit trail containing:
docs/source/component-spec.md:72:### 3.5 No Invisible Business Logic
docs/source/component-spec.md:76:### 3.6 Document Completeness Before Money Movement
docs/source/component-spec.md:84:- Required documentation completed.
docs/source/component-spec.md:90:### 3.7 Consistent Data Capture
docs/source/component-spec.md:92:Components should use shared primitives for member selection, date selection, currency, document upload, signature status, approval decisions, reason capture, comments, audit logs and task assignment. This avoids duplicate logic across modules.
docs/source/component-spec.md:94:### 3.8 Borrower-Friendly Communication
docs/source/component-spec.md:96:Borrower-facing content components must use clear, simple and localisable language. They must communicate application status, deficiencies, rejection reasons, sanction details, document requirements, disbursement advice, interest changes, reminders, NOC issuance and grievance responses.
docs/source/component-spec.md:98:### 3.9 Accessibility and Field Usability
docs/source/component-spec.md:108:- Low-bandwidth tolerance for document uploads.
docs/source/component-spec.md:110:### 3.10 Configurability for Policy Changes
docs/source/component-spec.md:127:## 4. Component Taxonomy
docs/source/component-spec.md:133:| Application Shell Components | Global layout, navigation, search, notifications and user identity. |
docs/source/component-spec.md:141:| Documentation Components | Document checklist, document generator, e-stamp tracker, notarisation, signatures, SH-4 and CDSL pledge. |
docs/source/component-spec.md:145:| Monitoring Components | DPD buckets, quarterly MIS, reminders, overdue dashboard and portfolio risk. |
docs/source/component-spec.md:148:| Compliance Components | Section 186 tracker, NBFC test, KYC audit, money-lending review, stamp duty and record retention. |
docs/source/component-spec.md:149:| Communication Components | SMS, email, hard-copy letters, borrower notices and internal notifications. |
docs/source/component-spec.md:156:## 5. Role Model and Component Permissions
docs/source/component-spec.md:158:### 5.1 Core Roles
docs/source/component-spec.md:162:| Deputy Manager - Finance | Application completeness check, KYC/document review, appraisal note preparation, borrower data entry, deficiency marking. |
docs/source/component-spec.md:165:| Company Secretary | Documentation approval, PoA handling, stamp duty compliance, security custody, statutory compliance, grievance log, recovery documentation review. |
docs/source/component-spec.md:172:| IT Admin | Role management, access control, SAP interface configuration, master data settings. |
docs/source/component-spec.md:173:| Auditor / Internal Auditor | Read-only access to audit trail, loan files, registers, evidence and compliance reports. |
docs/source/component-spec.md:176:### 5.2 Permission Patterns
docs/source/component-spec.md:189:| View Sensitive | User can see KYC, bank and security documents. |
docs/source/component-spec.md:190:| Download Sensitive | User can download sensitive documents where permitted. |
docs/source/component-spec.md:194:### 5.3 Role-Aware Component Behaviour
docs/source/component-spec.md:203:| Redacted | Sensitive fields masked or hidden, such as Aadhaar, PAN, bank account, cheque details and security document scans. |
