docs/source/component-spec.md:3857:## 32. Summary
docs/source/component-spec.md:3859:The component architecture for SFPCL's Member Credit Administration and Settlement system must support a highly controlled lending lifecycle. The critical design requirement is not only to capture forms and documents, but to enforce the sequence of controls embedded in the SOP.
docs/source/component-spec.md:3873:11. Compliance, reporting and audit components.
docs/source/component-spec.md:3875:A successful implementation should allow every loan to be traced from application number `LO00000001` style registration through sanction, documentation, SAP setup, RBL bank disbursement, repayment, monitoring, default handling if needed, closure and eight-year archive. The system should prevent unauthorised lending, incomplete document execution, premature disbursement and undocumented recovery action while keeping operational work manageable for Credit, Compliance, Treasury, Finance, Sanction Committee and audit users.
docs/source/data-model.md:1:# Data Model — SFPCL Member Credit Administration & Loan Disbursement Platform
docs/source/data-model.md:3:## 1. Document Control
docs/source/data-model.md:9:| Business domain | Member lending, credit administration, sanction, documentation, disbursement, repayment, monitoring, recovery, closure and compliance |
docs/source/data-model.md:11:| Source basis | Uploaded SOP documents and the current analysis set: client brief, user flows, functional specification, information architecture, screen specification, content specification, component specification, design system and domain model |
docs/source/data-model.md:14:| Recommended database style | Relational database with strict transactional integrity, audit logging, role-based access and encrypted sensitive data |
docs/source/data-model.md:19:## 2. Purpose
docs/source/data-model.md:21:This document defines the detailed data model for the SFPCL loan administration system.
docs/source/data-model.md:30:- Share valuation and loan-limit configuration.
docs/source/data-model.md:34:- KYC and document verification.
docs/source/data-model.md:57:## 3. Modelling Philosophy
docs/source/data-model.md:59:## 3.1 Key Principles
docs/source/data-model.md:63:| Compliance-first | Every critical action must have an owner, timestamp, evidence and audit trail. |
docs/source/data-model.md:67:| Configurable rules | Interest rates, approval thresholds, scale of finance, share valuation percentage, retention periods and TATs should be stored as versioned configuration. |
docs/source/data-model.md:68:| Strong workflow states | Application, documentation, approval, disbursement, repayment, default and closure states should be explicit. |
docs/source/data-model.md:70:| Physical and digital evidence | Many SOP controls depend on physical documents; the system must track both digital files and physical custody. |
docs/source/data-model.md:76:## 4. Recommended Technology Assumptions
docs/source/data-model.md:92:| Versioning | Effective-dated configuration tables |
docs/source/data-model.md:93:| Reporting | Use materialized views / reporting tables for portfolio and compliance dashboards |
